[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1485},["ShallowReactive",2],{"post":3,"content-query-YBjcu4IFOI":837},{"_path":4,"_dir":5,"_draft":6,"_partial":6,"_locale":7,"title":8,"description":9,"imagesource":10,"imagecredit":10,"image":11,"createdAt":12,"updatedAt":12,"readingTime":13,"body":18,"_type":831,"_id":832,"_source":833,"_file":834,"_stem":835,"_extension":836},"/posts/charlieplexing-leds-arduino","posts",false,"","Charlieplexing LEDs on the Arduino","How to charlieplex 6 LEDs, with PWM using only 3 pins on the Arduino.",null,"2012.01.15T150000_charlieplexing-leds-arduino.png","2012-01-15T15:00:00",{"text":14,"minutes":15,"time":16,"words":17},"1 min read",0.66,39600,132,{"type":19,"children":20,"toc":829},"root",[21,29,40,49,62,92,97,102,120,139,154,178,183,188,193,783,788,793,808,813,818,823],{"type":22,"tag":23,"props":24,"children":25},"element","p",{},[26],{"type":27,"value":28},"text","Another Arduino tutorial today - Charlieplexing!",{"type":22,"tag":23,"props":30,"children":31},{},[32],{"type":22,"tag":33,"props":34,"children":37},"a",{"href":35,"target":36},"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlieplexing","_blank",[38],{"type":27,"value":39},"Wikipedia says:",{"type":22,"tag":41,"props":42,"children":43},"blockquote",{},[44],{"type":22,"tag":23,"props":45,"children":46},{},[47],{"type":27,"value":48},"Charlieplexing is a technique proposed in early 1995 by Charlie Allen at Maxim Integrated Products for driving a multiplexed display in which relatively few I/O pins on a microcontroller are used to drive an array of LEDs.",{"type":22,"tag":23,"props":50,"children":51},{},[52,54,60],{"type":27,"value":53},"Basically, it allows you to take a number of pins ",{"type":22,"tag":55,"props":56,"children":57},"em",{},[58],{"type":27,"value":59},"n",{"type":27,"value":61},", and drive n(n-1) LEDs from them. Using this formula, you can see that as the number of pins increases, the number of LEDs also increases, but exponentially. For example:",{"type":22,"tag":63,"props":64,"children":65},"ul",{},[66,72,77,82,87],{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":68,"children":69},"li",{},[70],{"type":27,"value":71},"2 pins will drive 2(2-1) pins (2)",{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":73,"children":74},{},[75],{"type":27,"value":76},"3 pins will drive 3(3-1) pins (6)",{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":78,"children":79},{},[80],{"type":27,"value":81},"4 pins will drive 4(4-1) pins (12)",{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":83,"children":84},{},[85],{"type":27,"value":86},"5 pins will drive 5(5-1) pins (20)",{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":88,"children":89},{},[90],{"type":27,"value":91},"6 pins will drive 6(6-1) pins (30)",{"type":22,"tag":23,"props":93,"children":94},{},[95],{"type":27,"value":96},"In more detail, the way charlieplexing works is thanks to a microcontroller's ability to put its pins into high impedance mode (on the Arduino, this is INPUT mode), effectively detaching that pin from the circuit completely. Other than the pin(s) set to INPUT mode, there will be two others, both set to OUTPUT. One of these will be set to LOW (the current sink), and the other will either be set to HIGH or a PWM value (the current source). Each combination of two different pins will cause one of two LEDs in the matrix to be lit, depending on which is the source and which is the sink. Today, I'm going to explain in explicit detail how to charlieplex 6 LEDs via 3 pins, as this is the point at which charlieplexing becomes useful, and before it gets horribly complicated.",{"type":22,"tag":23,"props":98,"children":99},{},[100],{"type":27,"value":101},"To start with, you will need:",{"type":22,"tag":63,"props":103,"children":104},{},[105,110,115],{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":106,"children":107},{},[108],{"type":27,"value":109},"6 LEDs",{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":111,"children":112},{},[113],{"type":27,"value":114},"3 220Ohm resistors",{"type":22,"tag":67,"props":116,"children":117},{},[118],{"type":27,"value":119},"A bunch of jumper wires",{"type":22,"tag":23,"props":121,"children":122},{},[123,125